<h1>History's Most Famous Art Thefts</h1>

  <div class="topImgs">
    <div>
    <img src="/img/isabella.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum Heist (1990) - Boston, USA</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>13 artworks, including masterpieces by Vermeer (The Concert), Rembrandt (The Storm on the Sea of Galilee), Degas, and Manet.</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Over $500 million — the largest art theft in history.</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>Two men disguised as police officers gained entry to the museum, tied up the guards, and looted the galleries. None of the stolen pieces have ever been recovered.</span></p>
</div>
<div>
    <img src="/img/monalisa.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Theft of the Mona Lisa (1911) - Paris, France</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>Mona Lisa by Leonardo da Vinci.</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Priceless (now insured for over $800 million).</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>An Italian handyman, Vincenzo Peruggia, stole the painting from the Louvre by hiding it under his coat. He kept it for two years before being caught trying to sell it in Italy. Ironically, the theft made Mona Lisa world-famous.</span></p>    
</div>

<div>
    <img src="/img/van-gogh.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Van Gogh Museum Robbery (2002) - Amsterdam, Netherlands</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>View of the Sea at Scheveningen (1882) and Congregation Leaving the Reformed Church in Nuenen (1884-85).</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Around $30 million total.</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>Thieves used a ladder and broke in through a window. Both paintings were recovered in 2016 in Italy during a drug raid.</span></p>
</div>

<div>
    <img src="/img/rotterdam.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Kunsthal Museum Heist (2012) - Rotterdam, Netherlands</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>13 artworks, including masterpieces by Vermeer (The Concert), Rembrandt (The Storm on the Sea of Galilee), Degas, and Manet.</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Over $500 million — the largest art theft in history.</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>Two men disguised as police officers gained entry to the museum, tied up the guards, and looted the galleries. None of the stolen pieces have ever been recovered.</span></p>
</div>
  </div>

  <div class="topImgs">
    <div>
    <img src="/img/scream.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Oslo Munch Museum Theft (2004) - Oslo, Norway</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>The Scream (1910 version) and Madonna by Edvard Munch.</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Over $100 million combined.</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>Armed men stole the works in broad daylight. Both were recovered in 2006, slightly damaged but restorable.</span></p>
</div>
<div>
    <img src="/img/stockholm.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Stockholm National Museum Robbery (2000) - Sweden</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>Three paintings — Conversation with the Gardener by Renoir, Young Parisian by Renoir, and A Lady and a Gentleman in Black by Rembrandt.</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Around $30-40 million.</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>Armed thieves stole the paintings at gunpoint and escaped by speedboat through Stockholm's waterways. All three works were eventually recovered in separate police operations over several years.</span></p>    
</div>

<div>
    <img src="/img/paris-moma.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Musée d’Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris Theft (2010) - France</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>Five masterpieces by Picasso, Matisse, Braque, Léger, and Modigliani.</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Over $120 million.</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>A lone thief cut through a gate and window overnight, bypassing a faulty alarm system. The paintings have never been recovered, and experts believe they may have been destroyed to conceal evidence.</span></p>
</div>

<div>
    <img src="/img/scotland.jpg">
    <p id="title">The Drumlanrig Castle Da Vinci Theft (2003) - Scotland</p>
    <p>What was stolen: <span>Madonna of the Yarnwinder by Leonardo da Vinci.</span></p>
    <p>Estimated value: <span>Around $50 million.</span></p>
    <p>Known details: <span>Two men posing as tourists overpowered a security guard and escaped with the painting. It was recovered in 2007 during a police sting operation in Glasgow.</span></p>
</div>
